## Important Conventions

### Naming

- **ViewModels**: `{Feature}ViewModel`
- **Use Cases**: `{Action}{Entity}UseCase` (e.g., `GetAccountGroupListUseCase`)
- **Repositories**: `{Entity}Repository` (interface), `{Entity}RepositoryImpl` (impl)
- **Screens**: `{Feature}Screen`
- **State classes**: `{Feature}UiState`
- **Mappers**: `{Entity}Mapper` (object)

### Code Style

- Follow Kotlin coding conventions
- Use Compose for all new UI
- Implement proper error handling with Result types
- Use coroutines for async operations
- Add proper test tags to UI components for testing

### Localization Standards

Follow guidelines in `.docs/guidelines/LOCALIZATION_GUIDELINES.md`:
- Use professional Indonesian terminology
- Preserve technical terms ("User ID", "Email", "Password")
- Follow capitalization rules

### Design System

Follow guidelines in `DESIGN_SYSTEM_RULES.md`: color tokens from `core-ui/Color.kt`, text styles from `core-ui/TextStyles.kt`, atomic components from `core-ui/`, minimum touch targets 48 dp + contentDescription.

## Security & Performance

- **SSL Pinning**: Certificate pinning configured in `OkHttpClientFactory`
- **ProGuard/R8**: Obfuscation rules in `proguard-rules.pro`
- ~~**AndResGuard**: Resource obfuscation enabled in release builds~~ — removed permanently in {{JIRA_KEY}} (AGP-9 incompatible, fork archived). APK resources +10-20% accepted as the new normal.
- **Play Integrity**: Device attestation via FraudDataCollector SDK ({{JIRA_KEY}}, Mar 2026)
- **Firebase Crashlytics**: Crash reporting and analytics
- **Biometric Auth**: Fingerprint/Face ID via `BiometricPromptManager`

## Common Issues

📖 **Full catalog:** [`.docs/common-issues/README.md`](.docs/common-issues/README.md) — subject-grouped index + Unified Save Protocol for adding new issues or memory entries.

> **Rule — session learnings ALWAYS go to the catalog.**
> When the user says "take lesson", "save this learning", "document this for the team", or any equivalent phrasing, the default destination is `.docs/common-issues/` (git-shared). Memory is personal scope and only teaches *future-me*; the catalog teaches the whole team. Only skip the catalog if the learning is strictly a personal preference (user profile, workflow quirks) — those live in memory only. Follow the Unified Save Protocol in the catalog README: scan for a related chapter first, then either append a dated sub-note or create a new chapter + add a row to the catalog index + drop a 1-line pointer in this §Common Issues.

### When to scan the catalog (2 gates, not 1)

1. **Lookup gate — every first user message (no "substantive" filter).** Scan catalog index + `MEMORY.md`; if any keyword overlap with the 7 subjects (`build-gradle` · `ci` · `firebase` · `kmp-ios` · `networking-auth` · `release` · `testing`), **open the matching detail file before answering** — even on meta/greeting messages. **Why:** "substantive" judgments misfire; the read is cheap and prevents re-discovery.
2. **Save gate — before writing any new learning.** Scan catalog + `MEMORY.md`; if a related subject exists, append a dated sub-note instead of creating a sibling.

### Inline quick-refs (short tips without a dedicated chapter)

#### KSP Version Warning
If you see "ksp-2.0.20-1.0.24 is too old for kotlin-2.0.21":
- Known warning, ignore; build succeeds.

#### Missing Credentials
If build fails with missing properties:
- Run `bash generate_credentials.sh development`
- Requires CircleCI access + valid API token.

#### Hilt Build Errors
If Hilt annotation processing fails:
- `./gradlew clean`, invalidate Android Studio caches, ensure `@HiltAndroidApp` on Application.
- Check module has `ksp(libs.hilt.android.compiler)` dependency.

#### Kotlin 2.x: drop `kotlin.incremental.useClasspathSnapshot` from your global gradle.properties
Sync emits `Deprecated Gradle Property 'kotlin.incremental.useClasspathSnapshot' Used`. The flag was a Kotlin 1.7 opt-in (default in 1.8.20+) and is **unsupported in Kotlin 2.x** — KGP always uses the ABI-snapshot path now. Repo's `gradle.properties` is clean; the line lives in your **user-global** `~/.gradle/gradle.properties`. Remove it (or replace with a dated tombstone comment). `kotlin.incremental=true` is a different flag and stays. {{JIRA_KEY}}.

#### `amar-liveness` version is owned by the Confluence skill page, not by either branch
When merging `epic/DS-*-poc-advanceai` ↔ `regress` and the `amar-liveness` line in `gradle/libs.versions.toml` conflicts (e.g. `1.2.0` vs `1.2.0-beta006`), neither side is automatically right. The canonical pinned version lives in [Agent Integration Skill: centralized-liveness-implementation](https://{{JIRA_HOST}}/wiki/spaces/SMB/pages/{{CONFLUENCE_PAGE_ID}}) (current production: `1.3.1`, AGP 9 baseline; skip `1.3.0` — Artifact Registry slot is permanently dead). Both branches drift; resolve by reading the skill page, not by picking the "newer-looking" version. Same rule applies to the iOS pin (`from: "1.2.0"` resolves to `ios-1.2.1`).

#### Render typed/enum-like API strings via a canonical helper, never the raw payload
A field that arrives from a typed FE/BE contract (`platform: "chrome"`, status enum keys, etc.) is *case-sensitive in code* but the UI must not reveal that. Render via a `displayName(value)` helper on the same enum that owns the icon/colour mapping — it title-cases known values, falls back gracefully on unknown — so a future BE casing drift (`"Chrome"` instead of `"chrome"`) never reaches the user as `"chrome"` text plus a globe icon. {{JIRA_KEY}} / `BrowserType.displayName()` for the reference shape.

#### `git pull` fails with `cannot lock ref 'refs/remotes/origin/Conflict/...'` — Bitbucket case-collision on macOS
Bitbucket has both `Conflict/epic_{{JIRA_KEY}}_development` (PascalCase) and `conflict/epic_{{JIRA_KEY}}_development` (lowercase) as separate remote branches. macOS APFS is case-insensitive by default, so git can't store both refs side-by-side and the second fetch fails with `is at X but expected Y` on whichever case lost the race. Fix: `git remote prune origin && git pull` — prune drops the stale entry, then the next fetch recreates the winning case. Don't `git fetch --prune` blindly inside CI; this is a local-clone artifact only. Same pattern hits `Conflict/epic_{{JIRA_KEY}}-beneficiary` and friends.

### Library Module Gradle Tasks (no flavor)
Library modules (`feature-*`, `core-*`, `libs-*`) have **no product flavors** — only `:app` does.
- ❌ `./gradlew :feature-modules:compileDevelopmentDebugKotlin` → `task not found`
- ✅ `./gradlew :feature-modules:compileDebugKotlin` / `:feature-modules:testDebugUnitTest`
- App module needs the flavor prefix: `./gradlew :app:assembleDevelopmentDebug`

### Test-Compile Reflex After Type Removal or Hilt-VM Ctor Merge
Two failure modes share one fix: `:module:testDebugUnitTest` won't run if a test file has a stale
import to a deleted type ({{JIRA_KEY}} `AccountBody`) **or** instantiates a Hilt VM whose ctor merge
added a new required param (`PreviewSelfieViewModel` + `saveDeviceInformationUseCase`). Main-source
compile and conflict-marker grep miss both. Reflex: run `:module:compileDebugUnitTestKotlin` after
any deletion/merge — the compile errors are the fix-up checklist.

### Kotlin `internal` Constants Consumed Cross-Module Won't Compile
Constants/objects declared `internal` in a `feature-*` module **cannot** be referenced from
another Gradle module (e.g. `app/Navigation.kt`). Symptom: "Cannot access 'X': it is internal in …"
at compile. Fix: drop the `internal` modifier (default = public). Hit during {{JIRA_KEY}} chat-widget
TTL wire-up where `ChatWidgetSessionStore.DEFAULT_DURATION_MINUTES` was needed by `app`.

### Adding a Timber Call to an Extracted Module May Break the Build
Standalone modules carved out of `feature-modules` (e.g. `feature-mobile-token` extracted
{{JIRA_KEY}}) do not always inherit Timber. Adding `Timber.w(...)` for the first time fails
`compileDebugKotlin` with `Unresolved reference 'Timber'`. Fix: add `implementation(libs.timber)`
+ `lintChecks(libs.timber)` to the module's `build.gradle.kts` (same pattern as `feature-modules` /
`feature-biller`). Always grep the module's `build.gradle.kts` for `libs.timber` before assuming
the dep is present in implementation plans.

### JaCoCo Per-Module Thresholds Live in `gradle.properties`, Not the Convention Plugin
`build-logic/.../jacoco-android-convention.gradle.kts` reads `jacocoMinInstruction` / `jacocoMinBranch`
via `project.findProperty()` (defaults `0.76 / 0.60`). Per-module overrides live in each module's
`gradle.properties`. Don't edit the convention plugin to ratchet one module — bump that module's
`gradle.properties`. A module that applies the plugin but ships **no** `gradle.properties` falls to the
default and fails the gate (2026-05-04 CI #19179 hit `lib-sign`, `core-testing`, `core-analytics`,
`core-messaging`, `feature-liveness`, `libs-permission`).

Local gotchas: `./gradlew runCoverageGate` errors `Task not found` on Gradle 9 — task is registered in
`gradle.projectsEvaluated{}`, configure-on-demand skips subproject eval. Use `:runCoverageGate
--no-configuration-cache --no-configure-on-demand` (CI unaffected). After a threshold bump,
`jacocoCoverageVerification` can show **UP-TO-DATE** (threshold isn't a task input); add `--rerun-tasks`
to force re-exec and see the `[CoverageGate]` echo line.

#### Unit Testing `UserDataStoreRepository` — DataStore singleton blocks direct tests
`saveUserSession()` instantiates `DataStoreRepository(context.userDataStore)` — the `preferencesDataStore` delegate is a singleton needing real `filesDir`, so `mockk(relaxed = true)` + `TemporaryFolder` fails with `NullPointerException: parent.path is null`.
- **Workaround:** test `TokenCacheManager` populate/invalidate contract directly; DataStore persistence is covered by existing tests.
- `EncryptionHelper.encrypt()` throws `InvalidAlgorithmParameterException` in JVM tests — mock `encryptionHelperType` if you must call `saveUserSession()`.

### `@OptIn(ExperimentalMaterial3Api)` Propagates to Every Caller of a Default-Param Sheet Composable
A `core-ui` composable that exposes `sheetState: SheetState = rememberModalBottomSheetState(...)` as a **default parameter** evaluates that expression at the **call site** — so every caller still needs `@OptIn(ExperimentalMaterial3Api::class)` on the enclosing composable, even though the wrapper itself is opted-in. Symptom: `compileDebugKotlin` fails with `This material API is experimental and is likely to change…` on the line that simply invokes the wrapper. Hit during {{JIRA_KEY}} when adding `ChatUnavailableBottomSheet` to `OtherFragment`. Fix: add `@OptIn(ExperimentalMaterial3Api::class)` to the calling composable, or expose the param without a default (force callers to pass an explicit `SheetState`).

